<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - 5 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER ES60-5 - DISASSEMBLE -
        MAINSHAFT, COUNTERSHAFT AND GEARS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="16">
        <title>MAINSHAFT, COUNTERSHAFT AND GEARS</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1301222">Figure 22 .</hotlnk>
        </para>
        <figure id="f1301222" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1301222" filename="../figg13/G1301222.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 22. Mainshaft, Countershaft and Gears</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. BAFFLE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. SPACER</callout1>
                <callout1>3. GEAR BAFFLE</callout1>
                <callout1>4. BEARING CUP</callout1>
                <callout1>5. BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>6. INPUT SHAFT</callout1>
                <callout1>7. INPUT SHAFT BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>8. 4TH-5TH GEAR SYNCHRONIZER</callout1>
                <callout1>9. SNAP RING</callout1>
                <callout1>10. THRUST WASHER</callout1>
                <callout1>11. 4TH SPEED GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>12. 3RD SPEED GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>13. 2ND-3RD GEAR CLUTCH GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>14. 2ND-3RD GEAR SYNCHRONIZER</callout1>
                <callout1>15. BEARING MAINSHAFT 2ND GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>16. MAINSHAFT 2ND GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>17. NUT</callout1>
                <callout1>18. FLANGE OR YOKE</callout1>
                <callout1>19. SPEEDOMETER DRIVE GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>20. SPACER</callout1>
                <callout1>21. REVERSE GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>22. 1ST-REVERSE NEEDLE BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>23. 1ST-REVERSE CLUTCH GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>24. MAINSHAFT</callout1>
                <callout1>25. 1ST SPEED GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>26. COUNTERSHAFT FRONT BEARING SPACER</callout1>
                <callout1>27. COUNTERSHAFT DRIVE GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>28. COUNTERSHAFT 4TH GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>29. COUNTERSHAFT 3RD GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>30. COUNTERSHAFT 2ND GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>31. COUNTERSHAFT</callout1>
                <callout1>32. COUNTERSHAFT REAR BEARING SHIM</callout1>
                <callout1>33. REVERSE IDLER GEAR SHAFT</callout1>
                <callout1>34. BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>35. REVERSE IDLER GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>36. SPACER</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place the mainshaft on a bench (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301223">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301223" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301223" filename="../figg13/G1301223.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Mainshaft on Bench</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a suitable puller to remove the output bearing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301224">Figure 24</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301224" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301224" filename="../figg13/G1301224.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Remove Output Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Always wear safety glasses when pulling components off a shaft to protect your eyes from any
                        flying metal pieces.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">This method insures safe removal without bearing damage (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301225">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301225" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301225" filename="../figg13/G1301225.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Safe Output Bearing Removal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the 1st-reverse clutch gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301226">Figure 26</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301226" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301226" filename="../figg13/G1301226.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. 1st - Reverse Clutch Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Wrong method (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301227">Figure 27</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301227" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301227" filename="../figg13/G1301227.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 27. Wrong Method</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Do not pull on the synchronizer to remove the bearing. Doing so could damage the synchronizer
                        and cause shifting problems in the unit.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">One of these methods should be used to remove the pocket bearing from the mainshaft pilot
                diameter (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301228">Figure 28</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301228" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301228" filename="../figg13/G1301228.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 28. Remove Pocket Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Alternate method for bearing removal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301229">Figure 29</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301229" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301229" filename="../figg13/G1301229.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 29. Alternate Method - Bearing Removal</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">After removing the snap ring, the 4th speed gear and washer may be lifted from the mainshaft
                (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301230">Figure 30</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301230" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301230" filename="../figg13/G1301230.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 30. 4th Speed Gear and Washer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the 3rd speed gear, thrust washer and snap ring (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301231">Figure 31</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301231" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301231" filename="../figg13/G1301231.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 31. 3rd Speed Gear Thrust Washer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove 2nd-3rd speed synchronizer (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301232">Figure 32</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301232" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301232" filename="../figg13/G1301232.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 32. 2nd - 3rd Speed Synchronizer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the snap ring and the 2nd-3rd speed clutch gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301233">Figure 33</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301233" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301233" filename="../figg13/G1301233.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 33. Remove Snap Ring</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Rolled involute splines provide easier disassembly and reassembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301234">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301234" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301234" filename="../figg13/G1301234.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 34. Rolled Involute Splines</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The 2nd speed gear contains loose needle bearings in its bore (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301235">Figure 35</hotlnk>). They are used to meet the required load capacity of the
                2nd speed gear.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301235" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301235" filename="../figg13/G1301235.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 35. Loose Needle Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the snap ring and 1st speed gear with the thrust washer and caged needle bearing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301236">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301236" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301236" filename="../figg13/G1301236.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 36. Remove Snap Ring</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Examine the mainshaft gear locks and the internal corners of the synchronizer clutching
                teeth for excessive wear that could produce gear jumping (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301237">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301237" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301237" filename="../figg13/G1301237.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 37. Examine Mainshaft Gear Locks</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
